.\CHANGELOG.md:16:- **Root cause (silent prefab-gen failure):** SW *unit* bundles rendered native in-game because their prefab materials referenced Unity's **built-in default/error shader** (`m_Shader: {fileID: 46, guid: 0000000000000000f000000000000000}`), which DINO's Hybrid Renderer V2 shader-guard rejects → 0 unit swaps. Three competing Editor builders existed; the dedicated unit builder `BuildSwMissingBundles.Build` resolved its source meshes via `AssetDatabase.FindAssets("<fbx> t:Model", "Assets/Models")`, but **`Assets/Models/` is empty** (no glTF importer in the project; the 44 `.glb` live under `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/raw/`). Every def hit `MISSING FBX → continue`, so the prefab was never regenerated and the build re-bundled the stale built-in-shader prefab (`Shaders 0.0 kb` symptom). Likewise `BuildAll.Run` only upgraded a material **inside** its `[skip] existing-prefab` guard, so all 75 pre-existing primitive prefabs kept their non-URP materials.
.\CHANGELOG.md:20:- **Verification (real, not "built N"):** Ran headless `Unity 2021.3.45f1` (one instance at a time, lockfile cleared): `BuildSwMissingBundles.Build` → `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.Generate` → `BuildAll.Run`, each `-logFile`. `sw-shader-report.log` shows **19/19 unit materials = `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`, 0 Standard**. The git diff of e.g. `sw-b1-squad.mat` confirms the on-disk shader moved from the built-in error shader (`guid 0000…f000…`) to URP/Lit (`guid 933532a4fcc9baf4fa0491de14d08ed7`, the URP `Lit.shader` GUID) with full URP material props (`_BaseMap`, `_SpecGlossMap`, `unity_Lightmaps`). Sample bundles rebuilt fresh: `sw-b1-squad` 23.5 KB, `sw-cis-aat` 23.5 KB, `sw-rep-clone-engineer` 47.9 KB — build log reports `Total compressed size 22.8–47.0 KB / uncompressed 103.6–152.6 KB` per bundle (NOT `Shaders 0.0 kb`). The `sw-rep-clone-engineer` prefab references material GUID `173ab220…` = its `-primary` URP/Lit material.
.\CHANGELOG.md:201:- **Star Wars bundles shipped primitive-placeholder prefabs instead of real meshes (#101/#947)** — The shipped `warfare-starwars` AssetBundles wired 64/75 bundle prefabs to Unity built-in primitive meshes (Cube/Capsule/Sphere, `fileID:10202`), so even a perfect in-game Harmony swap rendered cubes. Root cause: `*.fbx`/`*.glb`/`*.obj` are gitignored, so in a fresh worktree the only committed mesh source is `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/raw/<asset_id>/model.glb` (the `!packs/*/assets/raw/*/model.glb` allowlist); the intended pipeline (`convert_models.py` Blender GLB→FBX → `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels` → `BuildAssetBundles`) was never reproduced end-to-end in the worktree, and the primitive-only generators (`GenerateStarWarsPrefabs.cs`/`BuildAll.cs`, which *skip existing* prefabs) had poisoned the prefab dir. Fixes:
.\CHANGELOG.md:203:  - Remapped three `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.cs` `ModelName` entries to real meshes that were previously unmapped: `sw-rep-at-te-walker`→`sw_aat_walker`, `sw-cis-spider-droid`→`cis_probe_droid`, `sw-rep-clone-commander`→`rep_clone_militia`.
